137: ## Performance Notes
138: The local seeded dataset currently contains:
139: - `2,287` raw events
140: - `2` stores
141: - `56` daily rollup rows
142: - `224` product revenue rollup rows
143: 
144: Measured locally against the running backend on warm requests:
145: - `GET /api/v1/analytics/overview`: ~`1.66ms` average
146: - `GET /api/v1/analytics/top-products?range=month`: ~`1.90ms` average
147: - `GET /api/v1/analytics/recent-activity`: ~`2.52ms` average
148: - `GET /api/v1/analytics/trend?days=14`: ~`1.71ms` average
149: 
150: Method:
151: - authenticate once with the seeded demo user
152: - hit each analytics endpoint 6 times locally with `curl`
153: - treat the first request as cold and report the average of the next 5 warm requests
154: 
155: ## Known Limitations
156: - Conversion rate is event-based, not visitor- or session-based.
157: - Mixed-currency reporting is intentionally out of scope for MVP.
158: - Rollups are daily, so the design is optimized for this dashboard rather than arbitrary drilldowns.
159: - Aggregates are updated synchronously on ingest. Under a flash sale for a single store, hot-row contention on the same daily rollup row would become a scaling limit.
160: - Authentication is deliberately minimal for a take-home and assumes one primary store context per demo user.
161: - The current `event_id` uniqueness model assumes globally unique event IDs across stores. If upstream producers only guarantee store-local uniqueness, the constraint should become `(store_id, event_id)`.
162: - Dashboard freshness messaging currently reflects the last successful fetch time, not a persisted database watermark.
163: - There is no separate backfill/correction job yet for late-arriving events.
164: 
